  "opinion": "As a transgender man who’s spent most of my life building things with my hands, I’ve always valued the physicality of reality—how wood grain tells a story, how a well-cut joint holds a structure together. That’s why fake content on social media feels like a kind of dissonance, a mismatch between the digital world and the tangible world I’ve lived in for decades. I spend about an hour daily on social media, mostly to stay connected with family and friends, but lately, I’ve noticed how often I stumble across posts that seem too perfect, too polished, or simply wrong. I used to be a bit skeptical of things that looked too good to be true, like when I’d see posts about ‘miracle cures’ or ‘secret diets’—back in my days as a carpenter, I knew that real work takes time, effort, and patience. Now, with my curiosity still high but my conscientiousness lower, I try to pause and ask myself: Is this something I can verify? Does it align with what I know from my own experience? For instance, when I see a post claiming to show a ‘real’ house built overnight, I remember how my grandfather would say, ‘A good house takes time to build, and it’s the little things that matter.’ I’ve found that reading novels and volunteering helps me stay grounded—these activities remind me that life isn’t about quick fixes, but about slow, thoughtful progress. So, managing fake content for me means being mindful, staying curious, and trusting my own experience rather than chasing the illusion of perfection.",
